WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
My name is Aaron Williams. I'm a senior data scientist at the Urban Institute. I make fake

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:16.639
data for a living. In some scientific circles this would be a huge scandal, but for me it's

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:22.160
an opportunity to further science. Administrative data, these are data that are collected for

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.000
reasons entirely other than research, like administering the unemployment insurance system

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.279
or enforcing the tax code, are incredibly useful for research, but understandably have

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:39.360
huge confidentiality concerns. I work at the Urban Institute. We're a collection of economists,

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:44.939
sociologists, criminologists, urban planners, and data scientists committed to improving

00:00:44.939 --> 00:00:50.080
the world through social and economic policy research. We would do a lot to access administrative

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:54.880
data, and we do do a lot to access administrative data, but we understand there's a fundamental

00:00:54.880 --> 00:01:01.040
tension between accessing these data and the confidentiality of the data. That's why

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:05.400
at the Urban Institute we've been working with the IRS to create fully synthetic tax

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:11.080
data. Synthetic data are fake data that have the statistical properties of confidential

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:16.919
data and could be used for certain types of valid analyses, but have much lower confidentiality

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:23.639
concerns because the data are fake. You can think of this as deep fakes for tax research.

00:01:23.639 --> 00:01:28.320
In this talk, I'm going to try and make the case that administrative data are very useful,

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:32.800
but are difficult to access. I'm going to share how we're working with the IRS to safely

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:37.639
expand access to administrative data for research, and I'm also going to talk about an R package

00:01:37.639 --> 00:01:43.440
that we're developing that makes it easier to synthesize data. Administrative data are

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:50.160
useful, and I'll give you two examples. The first example comes from March of 2020. It

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:54.440
was a scary time when there was a health crisis and an economic crisis unfolding at

00:01:54.440 --> 00:02:00.000
the same time. One issue, though, is that a lot of our indicators for the labor market

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.800
are backward-looking, and so there's one indicator, one number that came from administrative data

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:10.639
that I think painted an excellent picture of the labor market. Many people had never

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:14.479
heard of it, but it ended up in a dramatic data visualization on the cover of the New

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:19.559
York Times. This is initial weekly unemployment insurance claims. If you look at the bottom

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:25.919
left, that starts in 2000, and it bounces about from 2000 to 2020, and then there's

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:31.600
this black swan event that just shows how scary of a time it was in our labor market.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:38.600
I'll give you another example. In 2013, Raj Chetty, Emanuel Saez, and co-authors released

00:02:39.839 --> 00:02:45.360
groundbreaking research about intergenerational mobility in the United States using data from

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:51.759
40 million anonymized tax records. This was really big research that deals with how Americans

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:56.960
see themselves. We have that desire for our children to be better off than ourselves.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:02.199
One of the things that they found is that place matters quite a bit. For example, the

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:06.800
probability that a child reaches the top quintile of the national income distribution, starting

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:13.800
from a family in the bottom quintile, is 4.4% in Charlotte, North Carolina, but 12.9% in

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:18.960
San Jose, California. I think I said North Carolina, San Jose, California. It's a really

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:25.600
big deal. But some people say that this research never should have happened. In a traditional

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:30.039
model with an agency like the IRS, you do correspondence research. You have to get your

00:03:30.039 --> 00:03:35.119
analysis plan approved. You may never actually see the data. You send off your code. They

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:40.880
run it on the data. They review the results and the like. What Saez and Chetty did was

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:46.279
radical and different. They actually became employees of the IRS. They had to go through

00:03:46.279 --> 00:03:51.839
an extensive background check, have their fingerprints taken, go through lots of training,

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:55.479
have all their results reviewed. I've been through this process. Let me tell you, it's

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:01.360
not pleasant at all. The question is, how can we get this understanding,

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:07.600
this value, this meaning from administrative data without all this inconvenience, all while

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:13.279
protecting confidentiality? That's why we're working with synthetic data. If we can create

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:19.040
fake data that match the statistical properties of the confidential data, ways of safely validating

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:23.200
the results from the synthetic data against the confidential data, then we can conveniently

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:28.779
unlock a lot of this potential. We've worked with the IRS to create two kind

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:32.480
of one-and-a-half data sets. The second one is still a bit of a work in progress. The

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:37.359
first one is called the Supplemental SIN PUF, PUF for Public Use File. It's a collection

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:44.559
of information that the IRS has about individuals who have not filed taxes and do not have an

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:50.480
obligation to file taxes. It's a novel data set that's going to be very helpful for understanding

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:54.839
the very low parts of the income distribution. The tax economists that I work with are pretty

00:04:54.839 --> 00:04:59.720
excited about it. Now, you may be asking yourself, the IRS,

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:03.359
what are all these non-filers doing in here? What about information that's gathered at

00:05:03.359 --> 00:05:07.600
places that maybe have one of these out in front of them? That's the second file that

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.880
we're creating. It's called the SIN PUF, and it's representative of all taxpayers in the

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:14.959
United States. Now, the first file that I mentioned had about

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:20.720
20 variables. This file has more than 200 variables, hundreds of thousands of observations,

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:25.600
and it comes from a complex survey with 25 different strata.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:31.339
Let's consider a much simpler example for now where we have four variables and two observations.

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:35.579
That's our confidential data set. The setup of what we're trying to do is create a new

00:05:35.579 --> 00:05:40.940
data set that has the exact same record layout. We're going to employ a sequential approach

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:46.260
to create this data set. The first thing we'll do is we'll sample sex with replacement. Then

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:51.059
we'll create a predictive model to predict age, conditional on sex. Then we'll create

00:05:51.059 --> 00:05:56.779
a predictive model to predict wages, conditional on sex and age. Finally, a predictive model

00:05:56.779 --> 00:06:00.380
to predict taxes, conditional on sex, age, and wages.

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:05.339
A lot of predictive models, and this is where I get to express my gratitude for Tidy Models

00:06:05.339 --> 00:06:09.339
and all the people who have worked on this. We heard some great things about it this morning.

00:06:09.339 --> 00:06:13.500
Tidy Models is a comprehensive framework for doing predictive modeling in R, and we use

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:18.059
it extensively. In particular, we use Parsnip quite a bit, which is an interface to different

00:06:18.059 --> 00:06:22.260
machine learning and predictive models, and Recipes, which is a really powerful package

00:06:22.260 --> 00:06:26.660
for feature and target engineering. Now, in the example that we're working on,

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:30.260
we need to do three predictive models. I gave you another example where we need to

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:34.579
do more than 200 predictive models. So we could imagine having an R script where it's

00:06:34.579 --> 00:06:39.500
model one, predict, model two, predict, model three, predict. But if you're going to go

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:45.059
all the way to 200 variables, that's going to become a real pain really quickly.

00:06:45.059 --> 00:06:50.140
So what Tidy Synthesis allows us to do is actually specify a whole sequence of predictive

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:55.019
models for generating synthetic data. It also allows us to do a few things very specific

00:06:55.019 --> 00:07:01.700
to data synthesis. One is it allows us to add additional noise to predicted values for

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:07.100
extra confidentiality protection. It allows us to specify constraints in the data, things

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:11.820
like individual income can't exceed family income or interest income can't exceed your

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:17.420
personal income. It also allows us to predict from our models in different ways, and I'll

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:22.859
talk about that more in a second. So simply put, Tidy Synthesis, the goal is all the power

00:07:22.859 --> 00:07:29.140
of Tidy models for data synthesis concisely with a few special tools.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:32.500
So what does this actually look like? I'm going to show you how we're going to synthesize

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:38.019
a data set today. I'm not going to synthesize unemployment insurance data. To the relief

00:07:38.019 --> 00:07:43.619
of many of you, I'm not going to synthesize tax data. We could imagine synthesizing electronic

00:07:43.619 --> 00:07:47.980
health records, or maybe we're a business and we're interested in unlocking information

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:52.059
from our customer data without sacrificing the confidentiality of any individual in our

00:07:52.059 --> 00:07:57.019
data. But I'm not going to do that either. No, instead, we're going to synthesize penguins

00:07:57.019 --> 00:08:01.720
data because penguins deserve privacy, too. So we're going to synthesize the Palmer penguins

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:07.299
data set. We already had a good introduction to this earlier. Right, so we have information

00:08:07.299 --> 00:08:12.100
about species and island and sex and these numeric measures, measurements of the different

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:15.540
penguins, and we're really going to focus on these numeric variables, and our goal is

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:22.260
to create synthetic data that match the layout of that confidential data. So we can start

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:27.220
asking ourselves some questions of what this should look like. If you have 200 variables,

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:31.700
what order should we use? Well, tidy synthesis has a function that employs different heuristics

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:36.380
that you can use to determine synthesis order. In this case, I'm going to use my extensive

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.340
knowledge of penguins, which is absolutely none, to determine that bill length is a very

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:44.580
important variable, and then we're going to synthesize the remaining variables in order

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:49.059
from most correlated with bill length to least correlated. Once we create this visit

00:08:49.059 --> 00:08:54.700
sequence object, it's going to be reused in a lot of other functions. What kind of algorithm

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:58.940
should we use for our predictive models? In this case, we're going to use a regression

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:03.700
tree, and this is where Parsnip really shines in tidy synthesis. So we just specify a regression

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:10.219
tree implemented with the R part engine. Now we need to specify that for all of our different

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:14.179
models, and this is where we're really saving on all that R code. In this case, we just

00:09:14.179 --> 00:09:18.580
specify that we want to use the R part mod for every single variable. There's three ways

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:23.500
to specify this. The first one is like this, where we use the same model for all variables.

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:28.219
Alternatively, we can specify a default and then override it for specific variables, or

00:09:28.219 --> 00:09:33.419
we can specify a different model for every single variable. What types of feature or

00:09:33.419 --> 00:09:37.659
target engineering should we use? In this case, this is where recipes really shines

00:09:37.659 --> 00:09:44.140
in tidy synthesis. We can specify any set of steps in recipes for our synthesis. In

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:47.059
this case, we're not going to use any feature or target engineering. We're just going to

00:09:47.059 --> 00:09:52.619
use this helper function, construct recipes, to basically construct a series of formula.

00:09:52.619 --> 00:09:57.820
Finally, how are we actually going to come up with synthetic data from our models? Now,

00:09:57.820 --> 00:10:02.219
if you just use the predict function, oftentimes you get a conditional mean or a conditional

00:10:02.219 --> 00:10:06.619
median. This actually makes for really bad synthetic data, because the data sets that

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:10.140
you're creating don't have adequate sample variance, right? You don't have enough variation

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:15.140
in the resulting data. So in this case, we're going to use a function called sample R part.

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:19.099
If you're familiar with regression trees, you navigate to your final node, and oftentimes

00:10:19.099 --> 00:10:23.219
you might take the mean of that node. Instead, we're going to sample from that final node

00:10:23.219 --> 00:10:29.979
to sort of get this prediction distribution. So I just walked you through two of the functions.

00:10:29.979 --> 00:10:33.659
There's a lot of other functions and objects in tidy synthesis that can control the synthesis

00:10:33.659 --> 00:10:38.940
process. There's noise for adding additional noise to predicted values. There's constraints

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:42.900
for elegantly enforcing constraints in the data. And there's replicates if we actually

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:49.619
want to synthesize more than one data set, which can be handled in parallel.

00:10:49.619 --> 00:10:55.020
Tidy models is lazy, right? You create a bunch of objects, but a lot of the computation doesn't

00:10:55.020 --> 00:11:00.020
actually happen until you use a tune function or a fit function. And tidy synthesis is the

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:05.700
exact same way. So much like you have a workflow in tidy models, we have a pre-synth object

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:09.539
where we bring together everything, and then the actual hard work starts when you run the

00:11:09.539 --> 00:11:14.140
synthesize function. This is where you go check Twitter, get your cup of coffee. If

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:18.500
you have 200 variables, maybe let it run overnight.

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:21.539
So I promised that we were going to synthesize some penguins data, and I have a quick video

00:11:21.539 --> 00:11:27.260
to show this off. In the right, you'll notice we have about 300 observations. If we wrote

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:31.140
all this code out, it might be a few hundred lines of code, but in this case, it's only

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:35.859
about 70 lines of code. I'm going to highlight everything and click run here in a second,

00:11:35.859 --> 00:11:39.380
and you'll see that it quickly gets down to the synthesize function.

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:42.700
Now if you've worked with the Palmer penguins data set before, I want you to close your

00:11:42.700 --> 00:11:47.059
eyes and imagine what that data set looks like. This will take about 10 to 12 seconds

00:11:47.059 --> 00:11:52.419
to run. And now open your eyes. Unless you have it perfectly memorized, hopefully this

00:11:52.419 --> 00:11:57.820
looks like what you were seeing in your mind, right? This looks like the penguins data set,

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:04.419
but it's entirely made up. It's entirely fake. So we have synthetic data. We're done, right?

00:12:04.419 --> 00:12:08.460
If this is all I had to do, I'd be very happy. I'd spend lots of time by the pool with a

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:12.859
drink and, you know, with the little umbrellas and everything, relaxing. But in reality,

00:12:12.859 --> 00:12:16.979
I spend most of my day saying, have we done a good enough job?

00:12:16.979 --> 00:12:21.260
We can imagine looking at this in a few different ways. I mean, on the surface, it looks like

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:26.299
the penguins data set. We can look at the univariate distributions for the four numeric

00:12:26.299 --> 00:12:31.380
variables. Here I have density plots for them, where the synthetic data are in blue and the

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:35.460
confidential data are in yellow. And you see that we pretty closely recreate the univariate

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:40.859
distributions for each of them. And in fact, we only have 300 observations. So any differences

00:12:40.859 --> 00:12:47.299
here could just be because of sampling error. We can also look at some bivariate relationships.

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:50.979
Here I have the relationship between flipper length and bill length, flipper length and

00:12:50.979 --> 00:12:55.419
bill depth, and flipper length and body mass. Again, the synthetic data are in blue and

00:12:55.419 --> 00:12:59.539
the confidential data are in yellow. And in all three cases, I think we do a pretty good

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:04.820
job of recreating the data. And in fact, if you fit regression lines, which I've done

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:09.099
here, they look almost identical.

00:13:09.099 --> 00:13:14.219
But maybe we're not satisfied. Maybe we want to specify a new synthesis and start all over

00:13:14.219 --> 00:13:18.299
again. The good news is we're not starting from the beginning. Just like how in tidy

00:13:18.299 --> 00:13:22.679
models you can reuse objects sort of over and over and over again, here we can reuse

00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:27.059
all of our objects from earlier, add some information about adding noise to our predicted

00:13:27.059 --> 00:13:33.380
values, add some constraints, and synthesize.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:38.619
So just as a recap, administrative data are useful but difficult to access. And I think

00:13:38.619 --> 00:13:42.080
there's a huge potential to understand more about our world if we can make it easier to

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.919
access those data.

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:50.239
As a proof of concept, we've created two fully synthetic data sets with the IRS. And we've

00:13:50.239 --> 00:13:56.400
built this package called TidySynthesis so that other agencies, nonprofits, and businesses

00:13:56.400 --> 00:14:00.119
can implement these methods without having to write, you know, thousands of lines of

00:14:00.119 --> 00:14:01.119
code.

00:14:01.119 --> 00:14:06.960
Now, the data privacy community, the synthetic data community are pretty small. And especially

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:11.599
they don't have that many statisticians or data scientists. So if this is something that

00:14:11.599 --> 00:14:16.440
gets you excited, if you're interested in joining the raft of privacy penguins, please

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:21.479
don't hesitate to reach out to me after this talk here in person, on Twitter at AWUnderground

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:24.640
or on GitHub. Maybe this could be you. Thank you.

